WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.160
 So now we're going to build a very simple browser and server in Python.

00:00:05.160 --> 00:00:14.400
 Okay, so import a library, import socket, and that just like, you know, import math or import whatever,

00:00:14.400 --> 00:00:21.480
 that pulls in a library into Python. Sockets are built into Python, it's very cool, and it's very, very simple.

00:00:21.480 --> 00:00:28.720
 So, we're, sockets kind of function like files, but they're files that we can send data to and receive data to,

00:00:28.720 --> 00:00:32.320
 but when you're using a file in Python, you've got to first open it.

00:00:32.320 --> 00:00:37.440
 And so, the opening of a file, of a socket, is really a two-step process.

00:00:37.440 --> 00:00:44.160
 First, you create the socket, and that socket sort of lives in your computer as an endpoint that's not yet finished.

00:00:44.160 --> 00:00:48.320
 It's the endpoint that you're going to send and receive data to inside your computer,

00:00:48.320 --> 00:00:55.760
 but then we have to actually make the phone call. So, socket.socket, and don't worry too much about this syntax,

00:00:55.760 --> 00:01:01.920
 we don't change it, socket.socket basically says make a phone, that's what we're making.

00:01:01.920 --> 00:01:08.560
 And then, mysock.connect, that second line, is dial the phone.

00:01:08.560 --> 00:01:16.480
 And we're dialing the phone to a domain name, data.pr4e.org, and a port in that domain name.

00:01:16.480 --> 00:01:24.720
 So, that is the call. Now, if we made a mistake, right, if we had, we were dialing and not talking to the right server,

00:01:24.720 --> 00:01:32.400
 or that server didn't exist, this connect would blow up, meaning we'd make a phone call, a data phone call to a server that doesn't exist.

00:01:32.400 --> 00:01:39.360
 That line is what's going to blow up. But, as you continue down to the next line, if you continue down to the next line,

00:01:39.360 --> 00:01:46.960
 if it gets that far, now you put try and accepts around this, but I don't want to keep this really short, so I'm not putting in all the stuff,

00:01:46.960 --> 00:01:52.640
 all the error checking. So, connect might blow up, socket.socket won't blow up, because it's like,

00:01:52.640 --> 00:01:57.280
 unless you don't have networking at all in your computer, but it's unlikely these days.

00:01:57.280 --> 00:02:06.000
 But, mysock.connect is like, dial the phone, dial the data phone to this endpoint, and it includes the port, the port 80 that we talked about before.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:13.840
 And now, we need to send a command. And in this command, it's exactly what we talked about before, it's exactly what we sent via telnet.

00:02:13.840 --> 00:02:21.200
 It's a get, followed by a space, followed by our URL, followed by a space, followed by a protocol HTTP/1.0,

00:02:21.200 --> 00:02:31.040
 and then we hit the enter. Now, it turns out, in network world, you actually hit two things, it's the /r/n is a return and a new line.

00:02:31.040 --> 00:02:37.200
 And you have to hit it twice, the enter at the beginning of the first line, and then remember we had to put that blank line in,

00:02:37.200 --> 00:02:44.640
 because to say no headers. Now, we would put, in between here, we'd put all our headers in there, if we were going to do that, but we're not going to do that.

00:02:44.640 --> 00:02:51.600
 And then you have to use encode, and encode means that the data sent across the internet is generally sent in what's called UTF-8.

00:02:51.600 --> 00:02:58.640
 Inside of Python, the data is in Unicode, so that you can put literally any character in a Python string,

00:02:58.640 --> 00:03:07.440
 and then preparing it to send it out across the internet, we kind of encode it into the more dense UTF, more compressed UTF-8 format,

00:03:07.440 --> 00:03:15.920
 rather than we don't send strings across the internet in Unicode in general. I mean, it's very rare, but you'd have to control both ends.

00:03:15.920 --> 00:03:23.040
 We want to send them in UTF-8, and so the string get blah blah blah, that's in the Unicode string in Python,

00:03:23.040 --> 00:03:32.640
 and dot encode says convert this into a UTF-8 string, and so command CMD is a variable that has a UTF-8 string in it.

00:03:32.640 --> 00:03:37.760
 And then we say send, now remember I said that you can simultaneously send and receive on these sockets,

00:03:37.760 --> 00:03:42.000
 but the protocol tells us whether the first thing we're supposed to do is listen or talk,

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:46.640
 and we're the browser in this case, and so we're supposed to talk first.

00:03:46.640 --> 00:03:53.920
 So we send the request out, and that's just like you typed it in Telnet, because in effect you're scripting Telnet.

00:03:53.920 --> 00:04:00.480
 Telnet, we liked Telnet in the old days because it was kind of like a socket, I could connect to any host, any port,

00:04:00.480 --> 00:04:05.600
 and type things and see if it's broken or not.

00:04:05.600 --> 00:04:12.800
 And then the protocol says once the server has received the first line, any headers, and then the blank line,

00:04:12.800 --> 00:04:18.720
 then it's to return it. So then the next part of this is we're going to have a little loop.

00:04:18.720 --> 00:04:24.640
 So the protocol tells us we are supposed to receive data until the socket's closed,

00:04:24.640 --> 00:04:31.280
 and at the bottom of that Telnet you saw that it sent a bunch of lines, like the four I think, and then it closed it.

00:04:31.280 --> 00:04:37.760
 That's what's going on here. We are retrieving data, and then this receive, this actually waits.

00:04:37.760 --> 00:04:44.000
 If the server's coming slower, the network is slow, this piece of Python will be, sit, sit, sit, sit,

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:50.560
 oh, got a little bit, got a little bit, up to 512 characters, it will wait until it's gotten 512,

00:04:50.560 --> 00:04:58.720
 or it's done, and it's got 100 or so. But the receive is a blocking, waiting operation in Python,

00:04:58.720 --> 00:05:03.920
 says give me up to the next 512 characters. Now usually the network's so fast that the Python doesn't even wait,

00:05:03.920 --> 00:05:11.760
 because the operating system already has it, but we get it, and if we get no data whatsoever,

00:05:11.760 --> 00:05:16.160
 that isn't our indication that the network connection, the socket has been hung up on,

00:05:16.160 --> 00:05:21.440
 closed by the remote server, and away you go. So that's why we are going to break if the length of the

00:05:21.440 --> 00:05:28.240
 data is less than one, and if not, we're going to simply print out the data, but we're decoding it,

00:05:28.240 --> 00:05:35.600
 and that's because the data that comes in is in UTF-8, but the print statement wants to print Unicode,

00:05:35.600 --> 00:05:43.040
 and so decode says, here's a variable that has UTF-8 in it, convert it to Unicode for printing inside of Python.

00:05:43.040 --> 00:05:50.080
 So because this data is externalized to us, we encode it before we send it, and we decode it

00:05:50.080 --> 00:05:56.080
 when we receive it, before we use it, because Python inside itself doesn't use UTF-8, Python inside

00:05:56.080 --> 00:06:01.920
 itself uses Unicode, which is awesome and a whole separate conversation. I'm just kind of bringing

00:06:01.920 --> 00:06:07.520
 that up to remind you how important it is, because we're not going to write much of this in Python,

00:06:07.520 --> 00:06:12.560
 really, and all this stuff is taken care of for us in web servers when we get to that point,

00:06:12.560 --> 00:06:18.960
 but it's just a good time to review Python's strings and Unicode and encode and decode,

00:06:18.960 --> 00:06:28.320
 because it's really important. So if you run this, and you've got it right, it runs pretty simply.

00:06:28.320 --> 00:06:39.680
 Let's get the color back. Get it back to yellow here. So if you run it in your system, Python socket1.py,

00:06:42.160 --> 00:06:47.680
 all the work is done up here before you see your first output, and then all this output that you

00:06:47.680 --> 00:06:52.560
 see is just this loop running. And what you see is really the exact headers that are coming from

00:06:52.560 --> 00:06:58.080
 this server, and then you see a blank line, and then you see the actual page that's coming out.

00:06:58.080 --> 00:07:03.200
 And you don't see it, but at the end here, the connection gets closed, and you break out,

00:07:03.200 --> 00:07:10.080
 and you're done. And then we close our end of the socket. The socket, the far end was already closed.

00:07:10.080 --> 00:07:16.960
 That's how we know to stop reading data. And then we hang ourself up so that our local system does

00:07:16.960 --> 00:07:23.120
 not end up with a bunch of half hung up phone calls. And so that's basically how we talk

00:07:23.120 --> 00:07:33.600
 to a socket in Python. Now, that was literally 10 years ago how I would debug applications. I would

00:07:33.600 --> 00:07:38.240
 like Telnet or write a little thing like that and dump all the headers. And that got really

00:07:38.240 --> 00:07:44.000
 tiring, really boring, really tiring. And so browser developer mode is going to be your friend.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:47.280
 In a way, browser developer mode-- and I'm going to have a separate video on this--

00:07:47.280 --> 00:07:52.480
 browser developer mode lets you look at the sent headers, the received headers, the received data,

00:07:52.480 --> 00:07:56.560
 the sent data, what URL it went to. And it's super awesome, especially because a lot of

00:07:56.560 --> 00:08:03.120
 web pages have like 40 to 150 request response cycles. So you don't want to debug them all by

00:08:03.120 --> 00:08:07.680
 hand. You just let the browser do its thing and say, what was that second one, and what went wrong

00:08:07.680 --> 00:08:13.360
 in the second one? I spend a lot of time when I'm debugging web applications using the developer

00:08:13.360 --> 00:08:17.520
 mode. And that's why I have a special little video that gets you familiar with it. And I tell

00:08:17.520 --> 00:08:21.600
 you, by the time you've done web stuff for a little while, you're going to know your browser

00:08:21.600 --> 00:08:27.280
 developer mode. So next, we're going to talk about writing code in the server to respond to these

00:08:27.280 --> 00:08:38.720
 requests.

